table-1586-572.caption: Notable Life-like rules
data: All patterns are phoenixes, meaning that every live cell immediately dies, and many patterns lead to explosive chaotic growth. However, some engineered patterns with complex behavior are known. .
This rule supports a small self-replicating pattern which, when combined with a small glider pattern, causes the glider to bounce back and forth in a pseudorandom walk.
Also known as Inkspot or Flakes. Cells that become alive never die. It combines chaotic growth with more structured ladder-like patterns that can be used to simulate arbitrary Boolean circuits.

Forms large diamonds with chaotically fluctuating boundaries. First studied by Dean Hickerson, who in 1993 offered a $50 prize to find a pattern that fills space with live cells; the prize was won in 1999 by David Bell. .

If a pattern is composed of 2x2 blocks, it will continue to evolve in the same form; grouping these blocks into larger powers of two leads to the same behavior, but slower. Has complex oscillators of high periods as well as a small glider. .
Similar to Life but with a small self-replicating pattern.
Symmetric under on-off reversal. Has engineered patterns with highly complex behavior.
Named after Stephen Morley; also called Move. Supports very high-period and slow spaceships.

Son of Penda. Restored Mercian dominance in England. First Christian king of all Mercia.
Son of Æthelred I. Probably poisoned.
Presumed son of Æthelred I (may not have existed).
Grandson of Eowa. Proclaimed himself King of Britain in 736. Murdered by his bodyguards.
No known relation to his predecessors. Deposed by Offa. Possibly burnt to death in 769 in Northumbria.
Son of Offa. Co-ruler, died suddenly a few months after his father.
Seventh generation descendant of Pybba, probably through a sister of Penda. Assumed the title of 'emperor'.
Son of Cœnwulf. Although he existed, his status as co-ruler and his murder are legendary. Canonised (St Kenelm).
Brother of Cœnwulf. Deposed by Beornwulf.

No known relation to his predecessors. Killed in battle against the East Anglians.
Briefly took direct control of Mercia after the deposition of Wiglaf. Also King of Wessex (802–839).
Restored. Although Mercia regained its independence, its dominance in England was lost.
Son of Wiglaf and son-in-law of Ceolwulf I. Probably co-ruler.
Son of Wigmund. Declined the kingship and was later murdered by Beorhtwulf. Canonised (St Wystan).
Daughter of Ceolwulf I, wife of Wigmund and mother of Wigstan. Appointed regent by Wigstan.
Claimed to be a cousin of Wigstan. Usurped the kingship and forced Ælfflæd to marry his son, Beorhtfrith.
Possibly a descendant of the C-dynasty, of which Ceolwulf I was a member, perhaps via intermarriage with W-dynasty. Lost eastern Mercia to the Danes in 877.

Chennai Beach station is close to Chennai Harbour. It is a terminal station for few of the North and West bound suburban trains and a terminal station for all south line and MRTS line suburban trains.

Chennai Central's main building is a terminal for outstation express trains and mails. Chennai Central's Moore Market Complex is a terminal for suburban trains on North and West lines. Park station of South line and Park Town station of MRTS line lie opposite to Chennai Central on the Poonamalle High Road. Both the lines of the upcoming metro rail will pass through Chennai Central Metro station which is being constructed underneath the Poonamalle High Road.
Park is a suburban station on the south line while Park Town is a station on the MRTS line. Both the stations are nearby and are also opposite to Chennai Central.
The Guindy metro station under construction lies abutting the Guindy suburban railway station

The MRTS line and Metro line 2 will be housed in different floors of a common station complex, which lies abutting the existing south line suburban railway station. MRTS is being extended from Velachery to St Thomas Mount, while Metro line 2 is under construction

Chengalpet is beyond the suburbs of Chennai, 60km away from the urban precinct or downtown. Three lines from Melmaruvathur, Tambaram and Thirmalpur converge at Chengalpet Junction. Chengalpet Junction is also a halt for long distance express trains and mails

table-1586-925.caption: Archaic
data: Cottagers were a step below husbandmen, in that they had to work for others for wages. Lowest order of the working castes; perhaps vagabonds, drifters, criminals or other outcasts would be lower.

A tradesman or farmer who either rented a home or owned very little land was a husbandman. In ancient feudal times, this person likely would have been a serf, and paid a large portion of his work or produce to the land-holding lord.

The definition of a knight depends upon the century in which the term was applied. In very early medieval times a knight was a common soldier; later as cavalry became more important the knight's role became more associated with wealth. By the seventeenth century a knight was a senior member of the gentry, and the military role would be one of sheriff of a county, or organising a larger body of military forces, or in civil service exercising judicial authority. He was a large land owner, and his younger sons would often be lawyers, priests, or officials of some sort.
A baronet held a hereditary style of knighthood, giving the highest rank below a peerage.
The peers were generally large land holders, living solely off assets, sat in the House of Lords and either held court or played a role in court depending upon the time frame referenced.
A member of the royal family, a prince, a close relative of the queen or king.
